Problem Statement: Concrete Strength Prediction¶

Objective:¶

To predict the concrete strength using the data available in file "concrete.csv". Apply feature engineering and model tuning to obtain a score above 85%.

Resources Available:¶

The data for this project is available in file:

https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/concrete/compressive

Attribute Information:¶

Given are the variable name, variable type, the measurement unit, and a brief description. The concrete compressive strength is the regression problem. The order of this listing corresponds to the order of numerals along the rows of the database.

Steps and Tasks:¶

Deliverable – 1: Exploratory Data Quality Report Reflecting the Following (12 Marks)¶

  1. Data types and description of the independent attributes which should include (name, range of values observed, central values (mean and median), standard deviation and quartiles, analysis of the body of distributions/tails. (2 Marks)
  2. Missing values analysis, Outlier detection, Duplicates check, Comment about if the zero values mean the null value here. (4 Marks)
  3. Using various plots, write the insights/observations about it. (6 Marks)

Deliverable – 2: Bi-Variate Analysis (8 Marks)¶

Bi-Variate Analysis Between The Predictor Variables And Also Between The Predictor Variables And Target Column. Comment On Your Findings In Terms Of Their Relationship And Degree Of Relation If Any. Visualize The Analysis Using Boxplots And Pair Plots, Histograms, Or Density Curves And Write The Insights/Business Understanding Of The Same. (8 Marks)

Deliverable – 3: Feature Engineering techniques (8 Marks)¶

  1. Identify opportunities (if any) to extract new features from existing features, drop a feature(if required) Hint: Feature Extraction, for example, consider a dataset with two features length and breadth. From this, we can extract a new feature Area which would be length * breadth. (3 Marks).
  2. Get the data model ready and do a train test split.
  3. Decide on the complexity of the model, should it be a simple linear model in terms of parameters or would a quadratic or higher degree. (5 Marks)

Deliverable – 4: Creating the Model and Tuning It: (15 Marks)¶

  1. Algorithms that you think will be suitable for this project.
  2. Use Kfold Cross-Validation to evaluate model performance. Use appropriate metrics and make a DataFrame to compare models w.r.t their metrics. (at least 3 algorithms, one bagging and one boosting based algorithms have to be there and try to achieve 90% accuracy on testing set). (7 Marks)
  3. Techniques employed to squeeze that extra performance out of the model without making it overfit. Use Grid Search or Random Search on any of the two models used above. Make a DataFrame to compare models after hyperparameter tuning and their metrics as above. (8 Marks)

Deliverable – 5:¶

Write the significance of the R2 score from the business perspective. Explain the effect of an increase/decrease in the R2 score on the business model. (4 Marks)

Deliverable – 6:¶

Write down the inference about the data analysis and write the recommendations which can be beneficial to the business based on the whole analysis. Also, write the reason for your recommendation. (8 Marks)

Deliverable – 7:¶

The marks for the score will be according to the following: testing score 90 -95 (5 marks), 85 - 90 (4 marks), 80 - 85( 3 marks), <80 (2 marks)

Observations:¶

Back to Index

Columns cement, slag and superplastic contain values zero in them. At this point of time, it might be worth checking with an industry expert whether its normal for these columns to contain a zero. However, since this option is not available, following assumptions were made based on the limited reading on the subject from the internet:

  1. slag and ash are some sort of impurities in concrete mixture and can ideally be reduced to zero. Their absence in concrete may indicate an improved quality of concrete.
  2. superplastic is an additive, and some builders may choose not to add it in the concrete.

Based on above assumptions, presence of zeros in these three fields is considered normal and we will not make any imputations to zeros in these columns.

Note: This note is written almost towards the completion of the project. After running models on raw data without any imputations, it was found that these columns are very weakly correlated to the target variable, and model performed well without making an imputation to these variales.

#Step6: Outlier Analysis: Method used: IQR

percentile_25 = {}
percentile_75 = {}
iqr = {}
lower_bound = {}
upper_bound = {}

for i in pdata:
  percentile_25[i] = np.percentile(pdata[i],25)
  percentile_75[i] = np.percentile(pdata[i],75)
  iqr[i] = percentile_75[i] - percentile_25[i]
  lower_bound[i] = percentile_25[i] - (1.5 * iqr[i])
  upper_bound[i] = percentile_75[i] + (1.5 * iqr[i])
        
        
print(percentile_25)
print(percentile_75)
print(iqr)
print(lower_bound)
print(upper_bound)
print("\n")

# Plotting correlation to analyze how target variable is correlated with other variables
def plot_corr(df, size=12):
    corr = df.corr()
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(size, size))
    ax.matshow(corr)
    plt.xticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns, rotation='vertical')
    plt.yticks(range(len(corr.columns)), corr.columns)
    for (i, j), z in np.ndenumerate(corr):
        ax.text(j, i, '{:0.3f}'.format(z), ha='center', va='center')

plot_corr(pdata)

The observations we can make from this plot,

  3. The older the cement is the more water it requires, can be confirmed by observing the colour of the dots. Larger dots with dark colour indicate high age and more water.
  4. Concrete strength increases when less water is used in preparing it since the dots on the lower side (y-axis) are darker and the dots on higher-end (y-axis) are brighter.

Back to Index

    rep_0 = SimpleImputer(missing_values=i, strategy="mean")
    cols=['water']
    imputer = rep_0.fit(pdata[cols])
    pdata[cols] = imputer.transform(pdata[cols])

Observations:¶

Back to Index

  1. RandomForest, GradientBoost, and Bagging algorithms performed better in this case. It is worth to note that without making feature selection and hypertuning the model parameters, these algorithms achieved an acceptable testing score, KFold_Accuracy, and lowest Mean Squared Error. RandomForest performed the best in all aspects.
  2. Linear Regression and SVC couldn't perform well. SVC was computationally expensive as well. Note: Linear Regression was used without polynomial features. It might be worth exploring if increasing value for hyper parameter degree improves the performance of the model.
  3. In most cases, K-Fold validation accuracy was slightly better than testing scores. This is considered as a positive outcome here.
  4. Overfit Models: A Question may arise as to which model can be considered overfit? Especially, in this case, can the models that are performing well (e.g. Random Forest / GradientBoost) be called overfit? While the answer to this question is very generic and subjective, following conclusions are made.

Note: While there is no rule on this, for the purpose of explanation, it is assumed that models having more than 10% difference in training and testing scores are overfit. It might also be worth noting that to avoid data leakage, K-Fold validation was performed, and in most models, K-Fold score was better than testing score.

  1. Decision Tree: Training score is almost 1. There is a difference of 14% in training and testing scores. Mean Squared Error is also high. It can be concluded that the model is overfit.
  2. RandomForest, Bagging: Training score is high. Around 8% difference in training and testing scores. Performed well in validation. Low mean squared errors. While there is a possibility that these models may improve by feature selection coupled with hyper tuning, current models won't be considered as overfit. However, bagging won't be considered for further improvement because its feature importance couldn't be found.
  3. GradientBoost: Training score is high, but not approaching 1. Less than 5% difference between training and testing scores. Definitely not an overfit model. It can be considered to hypertune parameters and improve the performance.

Final Conclusion: Consider RandomForest and GradientBoost for further analysis / enhancements.

What is R-Squared?¶

R-squared is a goodness-of-fit measure for linear regression models. This statistic indicates the percentage of the variance in the dependent variable that the independent variables explain collectively. R-squared measures the strength of the relationship between your model and the dependent variable on a convenient 0 – 100% scale. Thus, R-squared is the percentage of the dependent variable variation that a linear model explains.

Why to use R-Squared?

After fitting a linear regression model, one needs to determine how well the model fits the data. Does it do a good job of explaining changes in the dependent variable? This can be achieved using R-Squared. R-squared evaluates the scatter of the data points around the fitted regression line. For the same data set, higher R-squared values represent smaller differences between the observed data and the fitted values.

What is ideal value of R2-Squared?¶

0% value of R2-Squared represents a model that does not explain any of the variation in the response variable around its mean. The mean of the dependent variable predicts the dependent variable as well as the regression model. 100% represents a model that explains all of the variation in the response variable around its mean. Usually, the larger the R2, the better the regression model fits your observations. There can be some limitations to this statement, that are not discussed here.

R-Squared And RMSE:¶

It is generally accepted by statisticians that a regression model fits the data well if the differences between the observations and the predicted values are small and unbiased. Unbiased in this context means that the fitted values are not systematically too high or too low anywhere in the observation space. To understand the difference between predicted and actual values of a target variable, RMSE is used.

RMSE:

Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) is the standard deviation of the residuals (prediction errors). Residuals are a measure of how far from the regression line data points are; RMSE is a measure of how spread out these residuals are. In other words, it tells you how concentrated the data is around the line of best fit. RMSE close to zero and R-Square approaching 1 (100%) are indicative of high accuracy between observed and predicted values.

In short, higher is the R2-Squared value, lower is the RMSE. Higher is the R2-Squared value, the model has better predictability (With some exceptions, e.g. an overfit model).

Conclusion:¶

We have analysed the Compressive Strength Data and used Machine Learning to Predict the Compressive Strength of Concrete. We have used Linear Regression and its variations, Decision Trees and Random Forests to make predictions and compared their performance. Random Forest Regressor and Gradient Boost Regressor have the lowest RMSE and highest R2-Squared. Therefore, they are a good choice for this problem. However,finally Gradient Boost Regressor was chosen. Performance of the algorithm was further improved by tuning the hyperparameters by performing a grid search or random search.

Based on the analysis of data, and at the end of the project, following are key takeaways and recommendations.

Note: Following is only the summary of the recommendation and observations throughout the project. Please refer to the section "Observations" at different points in this project for an in-depth analysis behind these recommendations.

  1. Strength increases as the amount of cement increases in the mixture.
  2. Strength increases with age, this not the case always (Since there are outliers in the data), but can be up to an extent.
  3. Mixtures with less age requires more cement for higher strength.
  4. The older the cement is the more water it requires. It might be worth to water the concerete as it gets older (e.g. exposure to rain).
  5. Concrete strength increases when less water is used in preparing it.
  6. Strength decreases as ash increases, therefore as ash can be considered as an impurity to concrete.
  7. Initial analysis suggested that strength increases with an increase in superplasticizers. However, it was contradicted by models. This area might be further explored (from the perspective of ML).
  8. The data, in and itself, was good enough to create a reliable model. Unnecessary imputations may cause an issue with integrity, and therefore, the overall quality of data.
  9. Complex models like Random Forest Regressor and Gradient Boost Regressor performed well without any major changes to data / hyper parameters. Therefore, it might be worth noting that whenever building model, best practice is to start with the defaults and then try to improve the model / data
